Appalachian Spring.

01:08:30.300 --> 01:08:34.190 position:56%
They together again in their '80s,
they were both thinking about legacy

01:08:34.190 --> 01:08:36.510
and how they were going
to keep their museum

01:08:36.510 --> 01:08:38.460
and companies going respectively.

01:08:38.460 --> 01:08:41.830
So they chose a few great iconic
settlements and they cast them

01:08:41.830 --> 01:08:45.300
in bronze and then they
each took half and sold them

01:08:45.300 --> 01:08:48.680
to help raise money to support
the museum and the company.

01:08:48.680 --> 01:08:54.620
And so we have a couple of those
but what we really would like to do

01:08:54.620 --> 01:08:57.050
and we're talking with Graham
about doing this and we're looking

01:08:57.050 --> 01:09:02.180
for joint funding is to reengineer
all the sets for the 21st century

01:09:02.180 --> 01:09:04.460
because every time Martha
Graham travels to Europe,

01:09:04.460 --> 01:09:07.970
it cost him about $40,000
to get the sets their

01:09:07.970 --> 01:09:10.120
and $40,000 to get them back.

01:09:10.120 --> 01:09:13.620
They take up a huge container
and they're very, very heavy.

01:09:13.620 --> 01:09:15.650
And they're so heavy
that they're not--

01:09:15.650 --> 01:09:19.220
they hurt them selves because
just moving them around back--

01:09:19.220 --> 01:09:20.880
the bigger something is
and the heavier it is,

01:09:20.880 --> 01:09:22.940
the more danger it is to itself.

01:09:22.940 --> 01:09:25.630
So we're really interested
in working together

01:09:25.630 --> 01:09:28.840
with a great industrial
designer to redesign them

01:09:28.840 --> 01:09:33.330
in some new material whether it's
carbon fiber or aluminum and use

