01:21:49.000 --> 01:21:52.520
We have a blueprint for
his redesigned of the camp,

01:21:52.520 --> 01:21:56.820 position:56%
which was basically kind of
turning it into Paris and, you know,

01:21:56.820 --> 01:22:00.630 position:56%
or as much as close as you could get
to Paris in the desert, in Poston,

01:22:00.630 --> 01:22:02.860
Arizona where it was
like 120 everyday.

01:22:02.860 --> 01:22:06.310
And-- But it was so horrible
and they had lied to him.

01:22:06.310 --> 01:22:08.490
So he wasn't able to do anything.

01:22:08.490 --> 01:22:11.010
And he was-- it turns out
he was totally out of sync

01:22:11.010 --> 01:22:14.950
with the job he's interned there
who we had nothing in common with.

01:22:14.950 --> 01:22:18.170
It was a nightmare for him and he
tried to get out after two months.

01:22:18.170 --> 01:22:20.370
But once they had him
they wouldn't let him go.

01:22:20.370 --> 01:22:22.680
And it took months
in the end for him

01:22:22.680 --> 01:22:25.900
to win his release even hough
he wasn't subject to interment

01:22:25.900 --> 01:22:28.040
because he was a resident
of New York.

01:22:28.040 --> 01:22:29.920
Not a resident of the West Coast.

01:22:29.920 --> 01:22:33.700
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: I think we have
time for one more if anybody.

01:22:40.090 --> 01:22:41.650
&gt;&gt; Thanks.

01:22:41.650 --> 01:22:43.510
When you were talking about
the high school he attended

01:22:43.510 --> 01:22:45.140
in Indiana [inaudible] understood

01:22:45.140 --> 01:22:48.300
that school had been
founded by the industrialist.

01:22:48.300 --> 01:22:51.110
And so there was a great focus
on getting the children to work

01:22:51.110 --> 01:22:53.080
with their hands and invent things.

01:22:53.080 --> 01:22:58.120
Was-- Did Noguchi begin
to work sculpturally

01:22:58.120 --> 01:22:59.860
or spatially at that age?

01:22:59.860 --> 01:23:03.530
I had read that he-- when he
was in med school at Columbia

01:23:03.530 --> 01:23:05.540
that he took a night
course in sculpture

01:23:05.540 --> 01:23:07.770
and that's where the flame was lit.

01:23:07.770 --> 01:23:09.250
But was it earlier?

01:23:09.250 --> 01:23:10.550
&gt;&gt; Dakin Hart: It was
much earlier than that.

01:23:10.550 --> 01:23:12.940
Yeah. And it's really all
down to his mother who was one

01:23:12.940 --> 01:23:14.650
of these figure like
Martha, you know,

01:23:14.650 --> 01:23:17.350 position:56%
is a person with just absolute will.

01:23:17.350 --> 01:23:22.210
His mother was a Bryn Mawr
girl, Irish-American stock

01:23:22.210 --> 01:23:24.780
and she was not married
to his father

01:23:24.780 --> 01:23:28.540
who is a famous Japanese poet,
but was editor, [inaudible] an ad

01:23:28.540 --> 01:23:31.090
in the paper, New York,
she's from Brooklyn

01:23:31.090 --> 01:23:37.160
and she followed his father,
Noguchi is born in Los Angeles

01:23:37.160 --> 01:23:40.830
and followed his father to
Japan, she spoke no Japanese,

01:23:40.830 --> 01:23:44.430
she had no job but she
decided that Noguchi

01:23:44.430 --> 01:23:49.610
who at the time was Sam Gilmore
because he actually was unnamed.

01:23:49.610 --> 01:23:52.780
They just called him Boy
for the first three years

01:23:52.780 --> 01:23:56.340
because his father wanted
to name him, you know,

01:23:56.340 --> 01:23:59.670
that was the father's
right to name the son.

01:23:59.670 --> 01:24:02.490
So they just call him-- well, they
had a bunch of different names.

01:24:02.490 --> 01:24:06.310
They call them Yo, which is
short for Yonejiro, his father's.

01:24:06.310 --> 01:24:09.050
But-- So he went Boy-- Yo and Boy.

01:24:09.050 --> 01:24:12.290
And so he finally got named
when she took him to Japan.

01:24:12.290 --> 01:24:16.100
But in the meantime his father
had started a Japanese family.

01:24:16.100 --> 01:24:18.400 position:56%
So they couldn't even stay with him.

01:24:18.400 --> 01:24:21.040
That was very awkward
and Noguchi spend--

01:24:21.040 --> 01:24:24.130
but Noguchi went to
elementary school in japan.

01:24:24.130 --> 01:24:28.780 position:56%
But his mother they built their own
house and his mother plan the house.

01:24:28.780 --> 01:24:30.990
Noguchi is about eight at the time.

01:24:30.990 --> 01:24:35.100
And Noguchi apprenticed to the
carpenter who is building the house

01:24:35.100 --> 01:24:39.650 position:56%
and learn to do basic planing and
sort of simple task that he could do

01:24:39.650 --> 01:24:41.460
as well as some decoration

01:24:41.460 --> 01:24:43.590
and he made some decorative
panels for the house.

01:24:43.590 --> 01:24:46.270
And he also did this
for his garden then.

01:24:46.270 --> 01:24:49.650
It really his first major work
was the garden around their house.

01:24:49.650 --> 01:24:51.500
And his mother gave
him that responsibility

01:24:51.500 --> 01:24:53.630
and said she wanted to
him to do the garden.

01:24:53.630 --> 01:24:57.030
And it's a wonderful story
because it had a water feature.

01:24:57.030 --> 01:24:59.930
But for the water feature he
needed a really good rock.

01:24:59.930 --> 01:25:03.480
And everyday he walked
across the neighbor's land

01:25:03.480 --> 01:25:06.890
and on the neighbor's land
there was a beautiful rock.

01:25:06.890 --> 01:25:08.590
And so he tells the story.

01:25:08.590 --> 01:25:09.890
It's just a lovely story.

01:25:09.890 --> 01:25:13.670
So he stole the rock and made
it a part of his water feature.

01:25:13.670 --> 01:25:17.230
And he said that as long as they
were in that house everyday,

01:25:17.230 --> 01:25:21.930
he feared that the neighbor would
come over and recognize the rock.

01:25:21.930 --> 01:25:25.530
Now Noguchi even at eight was
a sort of person who thought

01:25:25.530 --> 01:25:28.390 position:56%
that people recognize specific rocks

01:25:28.390 --> 01:25:30.970
because he recognized
specific rocks.

01:25:30.970 --> 01:25:33.490
He recognized the quality
of this rock.

01:25:33.490 --> 01:25:36.730
And so from his point of view he
had stolen this neighbor's greatest

01:25:36.730 --> 01:25:41.580
treasure to make the center piece
of his garden and he would continue

01:25:41.580 --> 01:25:45.370
to do that as we saw with the
Chase Manhattan sunken garden.

01:25:45.370 --> 01:25:48.110
He bought all that rock
before he had the job.

01:25:48.110 --> 01:25:53.580
And then he used it as leverage to
guilt his friend, the architect,

01:25:53.580 --> 01:25:57.470
into making sure that he got the
job, because he's already taken all

01:25:57.470 --> 01:26:01.960
of this rock out of Uji
River to do the commission.

01:26:01.960 --> 01:26:03.570
So he was thinking about
it for a long time.

01:26:03.570 --> 01:26:08.080
And the school only, you know, it
only increased and the clock case

01:26:08.080 --> 01:26:11.340
that I mentioned called
"Measured Time" was a commission

01:26:11.340 --> 01:26:16.900
from that man, Ed Grimley who
was his first great mentor

01:26:16.900 --> 01:26:18.850
and really supported him.

01:26:18.850 --> 01:26:22.560
Noguchi was a genius for
biting the hand that fed him.

01:26:22.560 --> 01:26:26.350
He designed this case for
Grimley and it was a big success

01:26:26.350 --> 01:26:27.660
but it was a high price point

01:26:27.660 --> 01:26:30.320
because it's a very
sophisticated shape in Bakelite.

01:26:30.320 --> 01:26:33.250
It was expensive to make and
Grimley said, "This is so great,

01:26:33.250 --> 01:26:34.550
we're making tens of thousands.

01:26:34.550 --> 01:26:35.850
They're selling.

01:26:35.850 --> 01:26:37.200
We want to do a cheaper version."

01:26:37.200 --> 01:26:41.180 position:56%
Grimley's vision was this was the
very first timer clock for the home.

01:26:41.180 --> 01:26:45.080
So for timing your Turkey it
had a 2 hour timer, wind timer,

01:26:45.080 --> 01:26:49.550
and it was based on timer
clocks from industry, you know,

01:26:49.550 --> 01:26:53.010
clocking clockout clocks which
were very, very accurate,

01:26:53.010 --> 01:26:56.290 position:56%
they were the most accurate ones
going, so he repackaged one of those

01:26:56.290 --> 01:27:00.150
for he home to go on every
stove in America, again,

01:27:00.150 --> 01:27:04.250 position:56%
[inaudible] thinking, efficiency and
improving the home and all of that.

01:27:04.250 --> 01:27:07.210
So Noguchi designed this
case, so Grimley asked him,

01:27:07.210 --> 01:27:10.310
"Can you design another one
that's less expensive to produce?"

01:27:10.310 --> 01:27:12.260
And then there's like all this
humming and hanging, you know,

01:27:12.260 --> 01:27:15.390
weather, like maybe kind
of possibly square-ish.

01:27:15.390 --> 01:27:18.140
And Noguchi wrote back to
him and said not only no,

01:27:18.140 --> 01:27:21.070
but hell no anybody
could make you a box.

01:27:21.070 --> 01:27:22.460
I won't do it.

01:27:22.460 --> 01:27:26.230
Maybe if you let me go back to the
original one I can make it better

01:27:26.230 --> 01:27:28.450
because Grimley had n
to let him model it.

01:27:28.450 --> 01:27:31.260
He'd had to draw it and then
it was produced from drawings.

01:27:31.260 --> 01:27:33.490
But he really wanted
to hand model it.

01:27:33.490 --> 01:27:36.410
So he offered to improve it, which
surely would've made it like two

01:27:36.410 --> 01:27:38.210
or three times as expensive.

01:27:38.210 --> 01:27:42.690
Sorry that was another
long digression

01:27:42.690 --> 01:27:46.100
